Document: Instancing
Path: godot/getting_started/step_by_step/instancing.rst
Summary: Explains the concept of instancing scenes in Godot, where saved scenes act as blueprints that can be duplicated and modified within other scenes.
Instancing scenes allows you to create reusable components in your Godot projects. A scene, saved as a .tscn file, acts as a blueprint. You can then create multiple copies, or instances, of this scene within other scenes. These instances behave like individual nodes, and while they start with the same structure and properties as their source scene, each instance can be modified independently. For example, if you create a "Ball" scene with a RigidBody2D, Sprite2D, and CollisionShape2D, you can then instance this "Ball" scene multiple times in another scene. Each instance of the ball will have its own unique name and can have its properties, such as mass or bounciness, adjusted separately from other ball instances.

Note: This tutorial focuses on instancing scenes within the editor. For instancing scenes via code, refer to the documentation on nodes and scene instances. Hardware instancing for rendering many similar objects is a separate concept and is covered in the documentation on using MultiMesh.
---CHUNK---
