Path: godot/getting_started/step_by_step/instancing.rst
Summary: Explains how scene instancing serves as a core design language in Godot, encouraging a component-based approach over traditional architectural patterns.

Scene instances and scenes in Godot provide a powerful design language. Godot was designed around this concept from the ground up.

It is recommended to set aside traditional architectural code patterns like Model-View-Controller (MVC) or Entity-Relationship diagrams when developing games with Godot. Instead, begin by conceptualizing the elements players will encounter in your game and structure your code around these visual components.

For instance, a shooter game could be broken down as follows:

This diagrammatic approach can be applied to nearly any game genre. Each rectangle represents an entity visible to the player. Arrows indicate which scene instantiates another.

After creating such a diagram, the recommended workflow is to develop a scene for each listed element. You will then use instancing, either through code or directly within the editor, to construct your scene hierarchy.

Programmers often dedicate significant time to designing abstract architectures and fitting components into them. A design methodology centered on scenes accelerates and simplifies development, allowing for a greater focus on game logic. Since most game components can be directly represented by a scene, a design based on scene instantiation minimizes the need for extensive architectural code.

Consider this example of a scene diagram for an open-world game featuring numerous assets and nested elements:

Imagine starting with the creation of a room. You could develop several distinct room scenes, each with a unique arrangement of furniture. Subsequently, a house scene could be created, incorporating multiple room instances for its interior. A citadel could then be constructed from numerous instanced houses, placed upon a large terrain. Each of these would be a scene that instances one or more sub-scenes.

Later, scenes representing guards could be created and added to the citadel, indirectly integrating them into the overall game world.

Godot facilitates iterative game development through the straightforward process of creating and instantiating more scenes. The editor is designed to be accessible to programmers, designers, and artists. A typical team development process might involve 2D or 3D artists, level designers, game designers, and animators, all collaborating within the Godot editor.
